An \ul access specifier\ulnone  is one of the following three keywords: 
\b private
\b0 , 
\b public
\b0  or 
\b protected
\b0 . These specifiers modify the access rights that the members following them acquire:\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}
\b Private Members
\b0  of a class are accessible only from within other members of the same class or from their friends.\
{\listtext	\'95	}
\b Protected Members
\b0  are accessible from members of their same class and from their friends, but also from members of their derived classes.\
{\listtext	\'95	}
\b Public Members
\b0  are accessible from anywhere where the object is visible.\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 we can refer within the body of the program to any of the public members of the object, 
\b object_names
\b0  as if they were normal functions or normal variables, just by putting the object's name followed by a 
\b dot (.)
\b0  and then the name of the member.\
\
The operator of scope 
\b (::, two colons)
\b0  : It is used to define a member of a class from outside the class definition itself.\
