\b\fs32 Constructors and destructors
\b0\fs28 \
\
A class can include a special function called 
\b constructor
\b0 , which is automatically called whenever a new object of this class is created. This constructor function must have \ul the same name\ulnone  as the class, and \ul cannot have any return type\ulnone ; not even void.\
\
The destructor fulfills the opposite functionality. The destructor must have \ul the same name as the class\ulnone , but preceded with a 
\b tilde sign (~)
\b0  and it must also return no value. Meanwhile, a destructor cannot have any argument.\
\

\b\fs32 Pointers to classes
\b0\fs28 \
\
It is perfectly valid to create pointers that point to classes. We simply have to consider that once declared, a class becomes a valid type, so we can use the class name as the type for the pointer. In order to \ul refer directly to a member of an object pointed by a pointer\ulnone  we can use the arrow operator 
\b (->)
\b0  of indirection.\
\

